---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';

const meta = {
  title: 'Webflow vs WordPress: Which Should You Choose? (2025)',
  description: 'Webflow vs WordPress comparison. Webflow is visual no-code. WordPress is flexible but complex. Which is right for your website? Honest comparison.',
  image: '/og-image.svg',
  keywords: ['Webflow vs WordPress', 'Webflow or WordPress', 'Webflow comparison', 'WordPress alternative', 'no-code website builder'],
};
---

<Layout {...meta}>

  <!-- Hero -->
  <section class="bg-[#FEF9F3] py-12 sm:py-16 md:py-20">
    <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4">
      <p class="text-[10px] sm:text-xs font-black text-[#E07A5F] mb-4 tracking-[0.3em] uppercase">
        Website Builders · Honest Comparison
      </p>

      <h1 class="text-3xl sm:text-4xl md:text-5xl lg:text-6xl font-black mb-6 leading-tight">
        Webflow vs WordPress
      </h1>

      <p class="text-lg sm:text-xl md:text-2xl text-gray-700 mb-8">
        Webflow is visual no-code with design freedom. WordPress powers 43% of the web but has learning curves and maintenance. Which should you choose depends on your technical comfort and long-term goals.
      </p>

      <div class="bg-[#E07A5F]/10 border-2 border-[#E07A5F] rounded-xl p-6">
        <p class="font-bold text-gray-900 mb-2">
          Quick verdict: Choose Webflow if you want visual design without code and have budget ($23+/month). Choose WordPress if you need maximum flexibility, want to own everything, and are willing to manage technical maintenance.
        </p>
        <p class="text-gray-700">
          Webflow is easier to learn but you're locked into their platform. WordPress is harder to learn but you own everything and can move it anywhere. The tradeoff: convenience vs control.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Quick Comparison -->
  <section class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 py-12 border-t border-gray-200">
    <h2 class="text-2xl sm:text-3xl md:text-4xl font-black mb-8 text-gray-900">
      At a Glance
    </h2>

    <div class="overflow-x-auto">
      <table class="w-full text-left border-collapse">
        <thead>
          <tr class="bg-gray-100">
            <th class="p-4 border font-bold">Feature</th>
            <th class="p-4 border font-bold">Webflow</th>
            <th class="p-4 border font-bold">WordPress</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td class="p-4 border">Type</td>
            <td class="p-4 border">Hosted visual builder</td>
            <td class="p-4 border">Self-hosted CMS</td>
          </tr>
          <tr class="bg-gray-50">
            <td class="p-4 border">Starting price</td>
            <td class="p-4 border">$23/month</td>
            <td class="p-4 border">Free (hosting extra)</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td class="p-4 border">Learning curve</td>
            <td class="p-4 border">Medium</td>
            <td class="p-4 border">Steep</td>
          </tr>
          <tr class="bg-gray-50">
            <td class="p-4 border">Design freedom</td>
            <td class="p-4 border">High (visual)</td>
            <td class="p-4 border">Unlimited (code)</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td class="p-4 border">E-commerce</td>
            <td class="p-4 border">Limited to medium</td>
            <td class="p-4 border">Unlimited (WooCommerce)</td>
          </tr>
          <tr class="bg-gray-50">
            <td class="p-4 border">Ownership</td>
            <td class="p-4 border">Hosted on Webflow</td>
            <td class="p-4 border">Self-hosted, you own it</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td class="p-4 border">Best for</td>
            <td class="p-4 border">Designers, portfolios, marketing sites</td>
            <td class="p-4 border">Blogs, e-commerce, complex sites</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Webflow Deep Dive -->
  <section class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 py-12 border-t border-gray-200">
    <h2 class="text-2xl sm:text-3xl md:text-4xl font-black mb-8 text-gray-900">
      Webflow: Visual No-Code
    </h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="bg-blue-50 border-2 border-blue-600 rounded-xl p-6">
        <h3 class="font-black text-xl mb-4">What Webflow Does Well</h3>
        <ul class="space-y-2 text-gray-700">
          <li>✓ <strong>Visual design:</strong> Build anything visually without code</li>
          <li>✓ <strong>Clean code output:</strong> Generates clean HTML/CSS/JS</li>
          <li>✓ <strong>CMS built-in:</strong> Content management system included</li>
          <li>✓ <strong>Hosting included:</strong> Fast, secure hosting on AWS</li>
          <li>✓ <strong>No plugins needed:</strong> Features built-in (forms, CMS, e-commerce)</li>
          <li>✓ <strong>Responsive design:</strong> Easy mobile/tablet breakpoint control</li>
          <li>✓ <strong>Interactions:</strong> Animations and micro-interactions are powerful</li>
          <li>✓ <strong>Designer-friendly:</strong> Feels like design tools (Figma, Sketch)</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-red-50 border-2 border-red-600 rounded-xl p-6">
        <h3 class="font-black text-xl mb-4">Webflow Limitations</h3>
        <ul class="space-y-2 text-gray-700">
          <li>✗ <strong>Platform lock-in:</strong> Can't export easily, stuck on Webflow</li>
          <li>✗ <strong>Price:</strong> $23+/month adds up (WordPress is free)</li>
          <li>✗ <strong>E-commerce limits:</strong> Not for large stores (WooCommerce better)</li>
          <li>✗ <strong>Plugin ecosystem:</strong> Limited vs WordPress's 60,000+ plugins</li>
          <li>✗ <strong>Learning curve:</strong> Still takes weeks to master</li>
          <li>✗ <strong>Template dependence:</strong> Starting from scratch is overwhelming</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-gray-100 rounded-xl p-6">
        <h3 class="font-black text-xl mb-4">Webflow Pricing</h3>
        <ul class="space-y-2 text-gray-700">
          <li>• <strong>Basic:</strong> $23/month ($192/year) - 2 sites, 5k CMS items</li>
          <li>• <strong>CMS:</strong> $39/month ($348/year) - 3 sites, 10k CMS items</li>
          <li>• <strong>Business:</strong> $87/month ($852/year) - 10 sites, 30k CMS items</li>
          <li>• <strong>E-commerce:</strong> Starts at $42/month + 2% transaction fee</li>
        </ul>
        <p class="mt-4 text-gray-700">All plans include hosting, SSL, and Webflow branding removal. Annual billing saves ~20%.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- WordPress Deep Dive -->
  <section class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 py-12 border-t border-gray-200">
    <h2 class="text-2xl sm:text-3xl md:text-4xl font-black mb-8 text-gray-900">
      WordPress: Unlimited Flexibility
    </h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="bg-green-50 border-2 border-green-600 rounded-xl p-6">
        <h3 class="font-black text-xl mb-4">What WordPress Does Well</h3>
        <ul class="space-y-2 text-gray-700">
          <li>✓ <strong>Free software:</strong> WordPress itself is free (you pay for hosting/domain)</li>
          <li>✓ <strong>60,000+ plugins:</strong> Feature for anything exists</li>
          <li>✓ <strong>Ownership:</strong> You control everything, can move anywhere</li>
          <li>✓ <strong>E-commerce powerhouse:</strong> WooCommerce is full e-commerce platform</li>
          <li>✓ <strong>Blogging built-in:</strong> Started as blogging platform, still best for it</li>
          <li>✓ <strong>Community:</strong> Massive community, endless tutorials</li>
          <li>✓ <strong>Theme variety:</strong> Thousands of free and premium themes</li>
          <li>✓ <strong>SEO capabilities:</strong> Yoast, RankMath - powerful SEO plugins</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-red-50 border-2 border-red-600 rounded-xl p-6">
        <h3 class="font-black text-xl mb-4">WordPress Pain Points</h3>
        <ul class="space-y-2 text-gray-700">
          <li>✗ <strong>Maintenance:</strong> Updates, security, backups are on you</li>
          <li>✗ <strong>Plugin conflicts:</strong> Plugins break each other constantly</li>
          <li>✗ <strong>Security:</strong> Popular target for hackers (security plugins needed)</li>
          <li>✗ <strong>Learning curve:</strong> Steeper than Webflow, more technical</li>
          <li>✗ <strong>Performance:</strong> Can get slow with too many plugins</li>
          <li>✗ <strong>Design requires coding:</strong> Visual builders (Elementor) help but are clunky</li>
          <li>✗ <strong>Host quality varies:</strong> Cheap hosts = slow sites</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-gray-100 rounded-xl p-6">
        <h3 class="font-black text-xl mb-4">WordPress Costs</h3>
        <ul class="space-y-2 text-gray-700">
          <li>• <strong>WordPress software:</strong> Free</li>
          <li>• <strong>Hosting:</strong> $5-50/month depending on quality</li>
          <li>• <strong>Domain:</strong> ~$15/year</li>
          <li>• <strong>Premium theme:</strong> $0-200 (one-time or yearly)</li>
          <li>• <strong>Premium plugins:</strong> $0-200/year each</li>
          <li>• <strong>Total:</strong> Typically $100-500/year for a solid setup</li>
        </ul>
        <p class="mt-4 text-gray-700">WordPress looks cheaper upfront but costs add up with premium themes, plugins, and good hosting.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Key Differences -->
  <section class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 py-12 border-t border-gray-200">
    <h2 class="text-2xl sm:text-3xl md:text-4xl font-black mb-8 text-gray-900">
      Key Differences Explained
    </h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="bg-gray-100 rounded-xl p-6">
        <h3 class="font-black text-xl mb-4">Ownership and Portability</h3>
        <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4"><strong>Webflow:</strong> Your site lives on Webflow's servers. You can't easily export it. If you leave Webflow, you're rebuilding from scratch. You're renting, not owning.</p>
        <p class="text-gray-700"><strong>WordPress:</strong> You own everything. Files, database, content - it's all yours. Move to any host anytime. Export/import is easy. Real ownership.</p>
        <p class="mt-4 text-gray-700"><strong>Winner:</strong> WordPress for ownership. Webflow is lock-in.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-gray-100 rounded-xl p-6">
        <h3 class="font-black text-xl mb-4">Ease of Use</h3>
        <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4"><strong>Webflow:</strong> Visual interface like design tools. Click to edit, drag to move. Intuitive if you've used Figma/Sketch. Still takes weeks to learn, but more intuitive.</p>
        <p class="text-gray-700"><strong>WordPress:</strong> Dashboard is functional but clunky. Visual builders (Elementor, Divi) help but feel dated. More technical overall. Requires understanding of hosting, databases, updates.</p>
        <p class="mt-4 text-gray-700"><strong>Winner:</strong> Webflow for ease. WordPress requires more technical knowledge.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-gray-100 rounded-xl p-6">
        <h3 class="font-black text-xl mb-4">E-commerce Capabilities</h3>
        <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4"><strong>Webflow:</strong> E-commerce is decent for small stores. Good for selling digital products, few physical products. Gets expensive at scale. Not for serious e-commerce (Shopify, WooCommerce better).</p>
        <p class="text-gray-700"><strong>WordPress + WooCommerce:</strong> Full e-commerce platform. Powers millions of online stores. Unlimited products, complex variations, subscriptions, bookings. More powerful but more complex.</p>
        <p class="mt-4 text-gray-700"><strong>Winner:</strong> WordPress/WooCommerce for e-commerce. Webflow for small/simple stores.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-gray-100 rounded-xl p-6">
        <h3 class="font-black text-xl mb-4">Performance and Speed</h3>
        <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4"><strong>Webflow:</strong> Fast by default. Hosting on AWS, optimized servers, clean code. Little configuration needed. Just works fast.</p>
        <p class="text-gray-700"><strong>WordPress:</strong> Can be fast but requires work. Caching plugins (WP Rocket), image optimization, good hosting, minimal plugins. Many WordPress sites are slow due to poor setup.</p>
        <p class="mt-4 text-gray-700"><strong>Winner:</strong> Webflow for speed out-of-the-box. WordPress with optimization matches or exceeds Webflow.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-gray-100 rounded-xl p-6">
        <h3 class="font-black text-xl mb-4">Maintenance</h3>
        <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4"><strong>Webflow:</strong> Almost zero maintenance. Webflow handles updates, security, backups, hosting. You just build content. Set it and forget it.</p>
        <p class="text-gray-700"><strong>WordPress:</strong> Constant maintenance. Update WordPress core, update themes, update plugins. Security scans. Backups. Break something, fix it. Never-ending upkeep.</p>
        <p class="mt-4 text-gray-700"><strong>Winner:</strong> Webflow by a mile. WordPress is ongoing work.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-gray-100 rounded-xl p-6">
        <h3 class="font-black text-xl mb-4">Design Flexibility</h3>
        <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4"><strong>Webflow:</strong> Visually design anything within constraints. No coding required for most designs. But you're limited to Webflow's features and capabilities.</p>
        <p class="text-gray-700"><strong>WordPress:</strong> Unlimited flexibility if you can code. Any design is possible. If you can't code, themes and page builders limit you. Code = unlimited. No code = limited.</p>
        <p class="mt-4 text-gray-700"><strong>Winner:</strong> Tie. Webflow for visual design without code. WordPress for unlimited flexibility with code.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Who Should Choose -->
  <section class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 py-12 border-t border-gray-200">
    <h2 class="text-2xl sm:text-3xl md:text-4xl font-black mb-8 text-gray-900">
      Who Should Choose What?
    </h2>

    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="bg-blue-50 border-2 border-blue-600 rounded-xl p-6">
        <h3 class="font-black text-xl mb-4">Choose Webflow If:</h3>
        <ul class="space-y-2 text-gray-700">
          <li>✓ You're a designer who wants visual control</li>
          <li>✓ Building a portfolio, marketing site, or blog (not e-commerce)</li>
          <li>✓ Budget allows $20-50/month</li>
          <li>✓ You want to build without coding</li>
          <li>✓ You want fast hosting and don't want to manage technical stuff</li>
          <li>✓ You're okay with platform lock-in</li>
          <li>✓ Maintenance-free appeals to you</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-green-50 border-2 border-green-600 rounded-xl p-6">
        <h3 class="font-black text-xl mb-4">Choose WordPress If:</h3>
        <ul class="space-y-2 text-gray-700">
          <li>✓ You need serious e-commerce (WooCommerce)</li>
          <li>✓ You want full ownership and portability</li>
          <li>✓ You have technical skills or willingness to learn</li>
          <li>✓ You need features only plugins can provide</li>
          <li>✓ You want to minimize long-term costs</li>
          <li>✓ You're building a complex site with custom functionality</li>
          <li>✓ You value flexibility over convenience</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Cost Comparison -->
  <section class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 py-12 border-t border-gray-200">
    <h2 class="text-2xl sm:text-3xl md:text-4xl font-black mb-8 text-gray-900">
      5-Year Cost Comparison
    </h2>

    <div class="overflow-x-auto">
      <table class="w-full text-left border-collapse">
        <thead>
          <tr class="bg-gray-100">
            <th class="p-4 border font-bold">Platform</th>
            <th class="p-4 border font-bold">Year 1</th>
            <th class="p-4 border font-bold">Years 2-5</th>
            <th class="p-4 border font-bold">5-Year Total</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td class="p-4 border"><strong>Webflow CMS</strong></td>
            <td class="p-4 border">$348</td>
            <td class="p-4 border">$348 × 4 = $1,392</td>
            <td class="p-4 border"><strong>$1,740</strong></td>
          </tr>
          <tr class="bg-gray-50">
            <td class="p-4 border"><strong>WordPress (mid-tier hosting)</strong></td>
            <td class="p-4 border">$200-400</td>
            <td class="p-4 border">$150-300 × 4 = $600-1,200</td>
            <td class="p-4 border"><strong>$800-1,600</strong></td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td class="p-4 border"><strong>WordPress (cheap hosting)</strong></td>
            <td class="p-4 border">$100-150</td>
            <td class="p-4 border">$60-100 × 4 = $240-400</td>
            <td class="p-4 border"><strong>$340-550</strong></td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>

    <div class="mt-6 bg-gray-100 rounded-xl p-6">
      <p class="font-bold mb-3">Cost Reality:</p>
      <p class="text-gray-700">Webflow costs more over 5 years but includes hosting, security, backups, and zero maintenance. WordPress appears cheaper but requires your time for maintenance. If you value your time, Webflow may actually be cheaper overall.</p>
      <p class="text-gray-700 mt-3">If you're technical and don't mind maintenance, WordPress saves money. If you want to "set it and forget it," Webflow pays for itself in time saved.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Final Verdict -->
  <section class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 py-12 border-t border-gray-200">
    <div class="bg-[#E07A5F]/10 border-2 border-[#E07A5F] rounded-xl p-8">
      <h2 class="text-2xl sm:text-3xl font-black mb-6">Final Verdict</h2>

      <p class="text-lg text-gray-700 mb-6">I use both. Here's when I choose which:</p>

      <div class="space-y-4 mb-8">
        <div class="bg-blue-50 rounded-lg p-4">
          <p class="font-bold mb-2">I choose Webflow for:</p>
          <ul class="space-y-1 text-gray-700">
            <li>• Portfolio sites</li>
            <li>• Marketing landing pages</li>
            <li>• Client projects where visual design matters</li>
            <li>• Sites that need to be fast with zero optimization</li>
            <li>• "Fire and forget" projects</li>
          </ul>
        </div>

        <div class="bg-green-50 rounded-lg p-4">
          <p class="font-bold mb-2">I choose WordPress for:</p>
          <ul class="space-y-1 text-gray-700">
            <li>• Blogs (still the best blogging platform)</li>
            <li>• E-commerce (WooCommerce is unbeatable)</li>
            <li>• Complex sites with custom functionality</li>
            <li>• Projects where I might need to move hosts</li>
            <li>• Budget-conscious long-term projects</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>

      <p class="text-lg text-gray-700 mb-6">The platform lock-in of Webflow is the biggest downside. If you're okay with that, Webflow is delightful to use. If ownership matters more than convenience, WordPress is the only choice.</p>

      <p class="text-lg text-gray-700 mb-6">My recommendation: Start with Webflow if budget allows and lock-in doesn't bother you. Start with WordPress if you need e-commerce, complex features, or want full control.</p>

      <p class="text-lg text-gray-700">Both are excellent. Wrong choice is annoying but fixable. You can migrate from Webflow to WordPress (painful but possible). You can migrate WordPress to Webflow (easier). Choose one, start building, learn as you go.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Related -->
  <section class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 py-12 border-t border-gray-200">
    <h2 class="text-2xl font-black mb-6 text-gray-900">
      Related Comparisons
    </h2>
    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
      <a href="/webflow-vs-framer" class="block bg-gray-50 hover:bg-gray-100 rounded-lg p-6 transition-colors">
        <h3 class="font-bold text-gray-900 mb-2">Webflow vs Framer</h3>
        <p class="text-gray-600 text-sm">Modern visual builders compared</p>
      </a>
      <a href="/ai-website-builders-compared" class="block bg-gray-50 hover:bg-gray-100 rounded-lg p-6 transition-colors">
        <h3 class="font-bold text-gray-900 mb-2">AI Website Builders Compared</h3>
        <p class="text-gray-600 text-sm">Durable, v0.dev, Framer, and more</p>
      </a>
    </div>
  </section>

</Layout>
